Your flex issue in short is that you're applying your flex value to each individual button rather than the containing View. If you want your buttons to wrap in rows when there's no more room left, change `{/{flex: 1/2}/}` to `{style={{ flexDirection: "row", flexWrap: "wrap" }}}`. Your updated `TimerSetupPage` function would look like:

```javascript
export default function TimerSetupPage() {
  const buttons = Array.from({ length: 10 }, (_, index) => ({
    id: index,
    label: `Timer ${index + 1}`,
  }));

return (
   <>
      <Stack.Screen options={{ title: 'Timer Set-Up' }} />
      <View style={styles.container}>
        <View style={{ flexDirection:'row', flexWrap:'wrap'}}>
          {buttons.map((button) => (
            <Button
              mode="contained"
              key={button.id}
              style={styles.button}
            >
               {button.label}
             </Button>
           ))}
         </View>
       </View>
     </>
   );
}

const styles = StyleSheet.create({
 container:{
    justifyContent:"space-around",
    paddingVertical :30,
 },
 button:{
     flexGrow :0,
     marginVertical :5,
 }
});
```

The parent view holds all of your Buttons now has `flexDirection` set as `'row'`, which determines the main axis of its layout along with `flexWrap` set as `'wrap'`. Meaning once space on this row runs out, items will move down to a new line.

